text=:Category: SignLanguage%0a:Essential: {Category.SignLanguage$:essential}%0a:Title: Different Types of Sign Language Acquisition%0a:Author: sgangu%0a:Section: A%0a:Completed: 07.05.2021 - 20:59%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210511-001630-234370#%0a* [-10.05.2021 - 17:16-] || TA_audrey marked as complete%0a#foxend 210511-001630-234370#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aWhether or not the parents of deaf children are also deaf can have a big impact on the way the children acquire the language.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aDeaf children of deaf parents are exposed to sign language early on in life, so the language acquisition here is compared to same milestones hearing children have with their spoken languages. They receive visual-gestural language from birth. Deaf children born to hearing parents don't have access to language in the same way. Occasionally, they develop their own system of signing to communicate. They have delayed access to their first language, but they can still develop it to mastery. Their home sign system becomes a first language and the sign language they learn in their deaf school becomes their second language. When tested on mastery and comprehension of ASL vocabulary, native learners performed better than people who learned a little later. Mastery was correlated with the age at which they were introduced to ASL. %0a%0a%0aSource: %0ahttps://www.oxfordhandbooks.com/view/10.1093/oxfordhb/9780199935345.001.0001/oxfordhb-9780199935345-e-19%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_audrey:)
